        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>7. Tarquinii Superbi historia tyrannica. Qui legum securus, Armoru[m] non satis curiosus. 
                        Nam aut magis iustum esse decuit; aut oportuit magis esse fortem.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tarquinius Superbus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Vsurpator.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Usurper.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Tyrannus.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Tyrant.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Techna[e] Regia[e], seu potius Tyrannica[e].
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>His royal or rather tyrannical skills.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Tarquinii Mnemosynon: non publici, sed privati Concilij celebratio. Vniversalia Concilia magis popularia: particularia, 
                        magis regia. Reges Gallia[e] ta[e]debat parlame[n]toru[m], cum coeperunt grandescere. Multa[e] utrinq[ue] cumulantur rationes, et autoritates, 
                        pro, et contra. Lysander stat ab eius parte, qui disputet acutissimo ense. Sed hoc argumentum valet de facto, non de iure. 
                        Ut sa[e]p&egrave; multa s[upr]a, i[nfr]a. Quae polychresta est pra[e]monitio.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tarquin the Elder"/>
                    <location name="Gaul"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Tarquin's record: the widespread use of private instead of public meetings. Universal assemblies are more devoted to the people, 
                and partial ones more to the king. The kings of Gaul were tired of their parliaments when they began to expand. From both sides many arguments and 
                opinions are heaped up for and against. Lysander stands on the side of the party that argues with a very sharp sword.
                Yet that argument has strength in practice [de facto], not in law [de iure]. As many [examples] below and above frequently show. 
                And that is a highly useful forewarning.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Veteratoria techna pragmatici tyranni.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The wily skills of the pragmatic tyrant.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Huc lex regia Romuli: huc iura Maiestatis: huc vnius, no[n] pluriu[m] imperium. Nec mal&egrave;; si ben&egrave; Rex, non Tyrannus. 
                        Si suis communiter consulat, non sibi propri&egrave; indulgeat. Monarchia non est confusum imperium, sed distinctu[m]. 
                        Et regis interest, singulariter / regere. Sed tam discret&egrave;, qu&agrave;m distinct&egrave; valet regnum, politicis principiis fundatu[m].
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Romulus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>About this point, see the royal law of Romulus; to this subject the rights of royal dignity; to this point the rule of one, not of many. 
                And this is not bad; if it is a king in a good way, not a tyrant. If he seeks advice from his subjects together and does not give in to his personal
                interests in particular. Monarchy is not a vague, but a clear form of government. And it is important for the king to rule alone. 
                But his rule is powerful in both a distinct and clear way when it is grounded in political principles.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
